t">3. What impacts have the FSS’s closure had on (i) the criminal justice system and (ii) forensic science R&amp;D and training? In particular, have the appropriate quality standards and accreditation been rigorously maintained? (please provide evidence/examples)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">4. What should be role of the Forensic Science Regulator?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Background</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> and the role of the Forensic Science Regulator </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The non-statutory role of the Regulator was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">first </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">described in a Written Ministerial Statement</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in July 2007:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“...</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">we have put in hand to establish the post of forensic science regulator, whose role </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">will be to advise Government and the Criminal Justice System on quality standards in the provision of forensic science. This will involve identifying the requirement for new or improved quality standards; leading on the development of new standards where necessary; providing advice and guidance so that providers will be able to demonstrate compliance with common standards, for example, in procurement and in courts; ensuring that satisfactory arrangements exist to provide assurance and monitoring of the standards and reporting on quality standards generally.”</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Clearly t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he role focuses on quality standards within forensic science. It does not deal with market or economic regulation nor does it deal with what could be considered service delivery standards. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I was appointed to the role in February 2008, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n performing this role I am supported by the Forensic Science Advisory Council (FSAC).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although my remit does not extend to Scotland or Northern Ireland, their respective authorities have agreed to join my work, and the FSAC, as full partners and, accordingly, to implement the resulting standards in their own jurisdictions. This will beneficially ensure the existence of UK-wide standards in forensic science.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is a feature of the role that I am expected to investigate complaints or concerns raised as to the quality of forensic science supplied to the Criminal Justice Systems in the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and to p</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rovide advice to Ministers, CJS organisations, suppliers and others as seems appropriate, on matters related to quality standards in forensic science</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In late 2009 I was asked to extend the role to include advice on the regulation of CCTV and was appointed as the Interim CCTV Regulator to advise on quality standards for the use of CCTV and on the future regulation of CCTV. In September this year I was appointed to the statutory role of Surveillance Camera Commissioner</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which is work I undertake in addition to the regulation of forensic science quality standards.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I agreed to the surveillance camera work on the basis that the recovery and use of surveillance camera (predominantly CCTV) images should be treated as a forensic process</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">; some police forces now refer to the use of CCTV images as ‘forensic imaging’. The role is to</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(a) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">encourage compliance with the surveillance camera code, </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(b) review the operation of the code, and </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(c) provide advice about the code (including changes to it or breaches of it).</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I am now in the position whereby some of my functions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> with regard to surveillance cameras</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are on a statutory footing with a role to encourage the use of a statutory code of practice</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, while others concerning forensic science quality standards are not. This point was discussed at the last committee session when I expressed a view that the forensic science role should be on a statutory footing. This view has since been endorsed by my Advisory Council an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d the Minister has committed to consulting on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> statutory powers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for the role.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Impact of the FSS Closure on quality standards</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">From the day the closure of the FSS was announced I advised the Minister that quality standards must be maintained with all work transferred from the accredited FSS environment moving </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to organisations that are equally accredited with a scope of accreditation cover</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ng the work they are taking on. The Minister fully supported and underlined this stance.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The transfer of work was managed by the Police and the National Policing Improvement Agency (NPIA) through a project known as Operation Slingshot. I advised the Slingshot team and helped them with the evaluation of the accreditation requirements. The net result was that work was only allocated to organisations who were suitably accredited.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">An example of the work I undertook with the NPIA and Slingshot team was the joint evaluation and comparison across the UKAS certificates of accreditation at different laboratories in order to evaluate the movement of FSS work. Following this I held meetings with the Slingshot </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">team to monitor progress. UKAS certificates of accreditation do not follow a standard template such that there is an immediate and obvious comparison across different laboratories; this is now changing through a programme of work led by UKAS to issue certificates against a standard template.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Accreditation is undertaken by the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) who were </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aware</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the transfer of work and monitored the impact on each organisation receiving</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> additional work to be sure that the volume increases were sufficiently managed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">an had no detrimental effect on the quality of the work delivered. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The transfer of evidence recovery functions into the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS) and the move of that activity from the MPS accredited facility at Amelia Street to the Lambeth site required that the MPS suspended their UKAS accreditation for this work while staff and procedures transferred to Lambeth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> where work commenced to the standards required in the absence of actual accreditation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> while such accreditation was evaluated by UKAS in the new laboratory and operating environment. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This was done with my</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> knowledge and agreement. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ccreditation has</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> since </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">been restored</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Similarly, LGC Forensics commenced some activities at the new facility supplied by the West Yorkshire Police in the absence of but after they had applied to UKAS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for accreditation. The work was done to the same processes and standards as those in accredited LGC laboratories. LGC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> now accredited for the work they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">undertake in West Yorkshire</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he police, NPIA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UKAS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> monitored the quality of work as it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">moved</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> from the FSS and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">were all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> committed to maintaining the required quality standards</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The Minister </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">monitored progress and standards through the Forensic Transition Board. The appropriate quality standards have been rigorously maintained.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Accreditation of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> laboratory activities</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Accreditation by UKAS provides formal, third party recognition of competence to perform specific tasks. Through accreditation an organisation can demonstrate that it has been successful in meeting the requirements of demanding standards. The police, CPS, laboratories and the judiciary support the use of accreditation.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further to the submission I made to the first committee inquiry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, I can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> report that the police, led by Deputy Chief Constable John Fletcher, have a programme of work to achieve accreditation of the police in-house laboratories</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and a vision to achieve a quality culture across all police forensic science activities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. This is supported by a project team that was formerly with the NPIA but now within the Home Office.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Nine police organisations (covering thirteen police forces) are now accredited.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> A further </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">twenty eight </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">applications </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">from other police forces </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are currently being processed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">by UKAS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">covering either new application</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> application</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to extend the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">scope</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> current accreditation.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I meet regularly with the project team and with DCC John Fletcher to monitor progress.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Home Office Centre for Applied Science and Technology have reviewed and updated their fingerprint manual which describes the methods to be used in fingerprint development laboratories. As part of this process they have re-validated all the methods and achieved UKAS accreditation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">all their published methods. This is a significant advancement in the move towards accreditation standards for fingerprint evidence and provides police forces with a solid foundation on which to build further quality management systems for fingerprint work.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Additional points</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">New standards have been agreed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> with me</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and jointly published with the Royal College of Pathologists for forensic pathology and my team has contributed to redrafting of the police Murder Investigation Manual covering pathology issues. We have successfully completed two audits of samples of work undertaken by all Home Office registered forensic pathologists.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Standards for crime scene activities have been successfully piloted by UKAS with the first organisation (Orchid Cellmark </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ltd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">) achieving accreditation. The standard is now available for any organisation to apply to UKAS for accreditation for crime scene activities.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Through a joint project with the British Standards Institution we have published a PAS (publically available specification – a form of British standard) which sets the requirements for consumables such as swabs and containers used in the collection, storage and analysis of forensic samples. The PAS is aimed at the manufacturers and suppliers of consumables and designed to help control and avoid the contamination of samples through inappropriate equipment.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Standards for specific disciplines, and intended as extensions to my codes of practice, have been drafted for DNA profiling, digital (computer and telephone) forensic activities, video analysis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and have recently been published for consultation. Standards for footwear comparison evidence, blood pattern analysis, entomology, drugs identification and firearms discharge residue have been drafted by experts and are soon to be published for consultation. Work has been commissioned for standards on the management and control of contamination in the collection and analysis of DNA, for fibres evidence, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">fingerprints</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, firearms, and tool</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">marks.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I have published detailed guidance for forensic science experts whose duties to the courts as expert witnesses are onerous and set out in a confusing combination of rules and case law. More recently I have published guidance on the legal issues in forensic pathology and tissue retention</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and a paper on the interpretation of DNA evidence. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> 201</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">3</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> House of Commons Hansard, 12 July 2007, Column 67WS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> S 34(1) Protection of Freedoms Act 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Surveillance camera codes issued under S 30 Protection of Freedoms Act 2012</span></p></body></html>